\emph default
.
 This one is subtler than it first appears.
 I was going to propose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}:[0,1]\rightarrow\R=\begin{cases}
0 & x\in[0,1-\frac{1}{k}]\\
k(x-(1-\frac{1}{k})) & x\in[1-\frac{1}{k},1]
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

, but that doesn't actually converge at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 (Note that the domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, is closed; we need to include the endpoints.) Then I thought of going with
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}(x):[0,1]\rightarrow\R=k\sin(2\pi x)$
\end_inset

, which blows up at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{3}{4}$
\end_inset

 (not on the endpoints) ...
 but that doesn't converge, either.
 Continuous functions on a compact domain 
\emph on
can't
\emph default
 be unbounded by the extreme value theorem! Therefore, the unbounded function
 we pointwisely converge to must not be continuous.
 Can we modify Axler's Example 2.83 to be unbounded?โbut again, if we make
 the peak 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitely high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we don't have convergence at the peak.
 We need to somehow push a peak up to infinity, while making sure that the
 limit function is defined everywhere (rather than failing to converge at
 the peak) and also making sure that none of the functions in the approaching
 sequence are discontinuous ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So I carefully engineered 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}(x):[0,1]\rightarrow\R=\begin{cases}
0 & [0,\,\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{k})\\
k^{2}(x-\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{k}\right)) & [\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{k},\frac{1}{2}]\\
\frac{1}{x-(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{k})} & (\frac{1}{2},\,1]
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

 , which I thought would work as the desired sequence of continuous functions
 that converges pointwise to an unbounded function: each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 is continuous (constant from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{k}$
\end_inset

, then linear from 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{k}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, attaining a peak of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=k$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, then hyperbolic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coming down
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), but (one would think) it converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):[0,1]\rightarrow\R=\begin{cases}
0 & [0,\frac{1}{2}]\\
\frac{1}{x-\frac{1}{2}} & (\frac{1}{2},1]
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

.
 But that's wishful thinking; when we actually calculate the limit at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, it's 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{k\rightarrow\infty}k^{2}(\cancel{\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{2}}+\frac{1}{k})=\lim_{k\rightarrow\infty}k^{2}\frac{1}{k}=\lim_{k\rightarrow\infty}k$
\end_inset

, which doesn't converge.
